<span class="header1">ANIMAL AND NATURE SCIENCES</span>
<p>Occupations in this field are concerned with studying and working with plants and animals. They are more "hands on" than occupations in the arts and communication fields. People in this field work to benefit the plants and animals in our environment. They should be active and enjoy being in nature and working outdoors.</p>

<hr size="1" />
	
	<span class="header2">Botanist</span><br /><br />
	<img class="job_pic" src="/images/icons/AB/1020.jpg" width="100" height="100" border="0" alt="Botanist" />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>Botanists study and work with plant life. If you would like to grow and harvest food plants, or work with trees, shrubs and flowers, you might become a botanist. As a botanist, you might work to improve plant yields.  You might find ways to regulate plant growth or develop stronger or disease-free plants. You might also teach botany in a high school or university, or work to protect plant life.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>A botanist must have at least a Bachelor's Degree for an entry-level job. Employers prefer a Master's or Ph.D. To learn more about plants, you can work in a plant nursery. You can also volunteer with groups concerned with the environment.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>Salaries run between $19,000 and $25,000 a year.</blockquote>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Zoologist</span><br /><br />
	<img class="job_pic" src="/images/icons/AB/1079.jpg" width="100" height="100" border="0" alt="Zoologist" />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>If you enjoy learning about and working with animals, you may become a zoologist.  Zoologists work in zoos and wildlife parks.  They also work in research centers and agricultural settings.  If you become a zoologist, you could help save animals or protect endangered species. You might also help develop better ways to raise animals for food, or work to produce better breeds of animals.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>A zoologist must have at least a Bachelor's Degree for an entry-level job.  Employers prefer a Master's Degree or Ph.D.  To find out if you enjoy close contact with animals, you might work on a farm, or in a zoo or pet store.  You might also volunteer as a veterinarian's assistant.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>The salary range is $29,000 to $71,000 per year.</blockquote>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Wildlife Guide</span>
	<br /><br />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>If you like teaching others about our environment, you may become a wildlife guide. People often tour parks, wildlife refuges and other natural areas. As a wildlife guide, you would point out the interesting features of such areas to these people.  You would need excellent public speaking skills to do this.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span> 
	<blockquote>You don't need a college degree for this occupation.  But you do need experience in the outdoors and a desire to share information with other people.  You can gain outdoor experience and skill in talking with others by working with groups concerned about the environment.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>The salary range is $13,000 to $18,000 per year.</blockquote>

