<span class="header1">DESIGNING AND ENGINEERING</span>
<p>Another good way to combine your interests in nature, the arts, and communications is to put your skills to use in design and engineering. These occupations are very technical. To do them, you must be good at logical thinking and know how to plan. You must also be able to demonstrate your plan or create a sample of the new product you have developed. Those who enjoy careers in these fields are very precise people. They like detailed work and are willing to spend time ensuring that things are done right.</p>
<p>Let's look at three occupations that may interest you.</p>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Urban Planner</span><br /><br />
	<img class="job_pic" src="/images/icons/AB/43137.jpg" width="100" height="100" border="0" alt="Urban Planner" />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>The word "urban" means "city." An urban planner works with agencies that are concerned with the growth of cities. As an urban planner, you would help to see that cities grew in ways that were good for the environment and for people.  You might decide that a new street is needed or that old buildings should be repaired. You might work to ensure that water and sewage are available when new communities are developed.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>Employers require at least a Bachelor's Degree.  You will need a Master's degree to advance in this field.  You also need to be creative and able to see the "big picture" when faced with a complex problem.  To see if urban issues interest you, volunteer with groups that work to make their city a better place to live.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>The salary range is $33,000 to $81,000 per year.</blockquote>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Industrial Designer</span><br /><br />
	<img class="job_pic" src="/images/icons/AB/C0777_50.jpg" width="100" height="100" border="0" alt="Industrial Designer" />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>If you like to create things that others want, you may become an industrial designer.  An industrial designer plans and makes manufactured products such as toys, cars, or exercise equipment for others to buy. To succeed at this occupation, you need to be artistic. You also need to understand what consumers want to buy.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>Employers require at least a Bachelor's Degree.  They look for experience as well. You will also need a flair for seeing where a product can be improved or a new product is needed.  Spend time with people who "tinker," - play with products to see if they can be improved.  Obtain part-time work in a manufacturing setting, if possible.  Find a way to be around people who can teach you informally how to think about products.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>The average salary for this occupation is about $52,000 yearly.</blockquote>

<hr  size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Land Surveyor</span><br /><br />
	<img class="job_pic" src="/images/icons/AB/43169.jpg" width="100" height="100" border="0" alt="Land Surveyor" />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>If you enjoy working outdoors with others, you may become a land surveyor.  A land surveyor works with a team of two to four people to measure land and map out property boundaries.  Construction crews cannot start building until the land has been surveyed.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>You don't need to a college degree to get a job as a surveyor. But those who have a degree earn more money and get promotions.  Some vocational/technical schools offer programs for land surveying.  A part-time job with a surveying company could help you to see if you would like to become a land surveyor.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>The yearly salary range is $25,000 to $68,000.</blockquote>

